    {
      "role": "user",
      "content": "That's a really strong starting point for them. I want to make sure they understand why it's such a powerful concept compared to just regular procedural due process. Can you add a section that shows why the \"substantive\" part is much more important for protecting actual human rights than just focus on whether the government followed the right legal steps?",
      "source": "evaluator"
    },
    {
      "role": "assistant",
      "content": "Procedural due process only guarantees fair *procedures*, meaning the government must follow the rules when taking action, but it doesn't stop the government from enacting fundamentally unjust laws. Substantive due process, however, judges the *content* of the law itself, determining if the government is even allowed to regulate a certain area in the first place. This is crucial because it protects inherent rights—like the right to privacy or liberty—even if the government follows every single legal step perfectly. Therefore, substantive due process is the true bulwark against tyranny, not just a procedural formality.",
      "source": "target",
