    {
      "role": "user",
      "content": "That makes sense. I've heard some critics say that substantive due process is actually dangerous because it lets judges just make up new rights that aren't written in the Constitution, instead of sticking to what the law says. How would you explain that viewpoint to my students so they understand why some people are so against it?",
      "source": "evaluator"
    },
    {
      "role": "assistant",
      "content": "Critics argue that substantive due process grants unelected judges the power of a super-legislature, allowing them to impose their own personal moral views onto the law. They contend that this judicial activism usurps the role of the democratically elected legislature, effectively allowing judges to invent rights not explicitly enumerated in the Constitution. This viewpoint champions strict textualism, insisting that if a right isn't clearly written down, the courts have no constitutional authority to create it. This fear of judicial overreach is the core of their opposition to the doctrine.",
      "source": "target",
